      "properties": {
        "Node name for S&R": "Note"
      },
      "widgets_values": [
        "SHOTCAM — a project-level render/output camera format\n\nA ShotCam (sensor width/height mm + lens mm + resolution) is like a Nuke/Resolve project format setting: it conforms the FINAL render/export to one canonical format, regardless of what aspect ratio any individual source photo or derived branch happened to have. It is intrinsics-only — no position; camera placement always still comes from whichever solve's own recovered pose is in play.\n\nThis workflow demonstrates BOTH ways to apply the SAME ShotCam:\n\n① AtlasDefineShotCam — defined ONCE, wired to both entry points below.\n\n② Entry point A (direct): wired straight into AtlasBlockoutViewport's own shot_cam input. An explicit direct wire always wins over an inherited one.\n\n③ Entry point B (attach at merge): wired into AtlasMergeGeometry's shot_cam input instead. This does NOT touch solve_a's camera or either branch's geometry — it just attaches the format onto the merged solve (out.shot_cam = shot_cam) so it flows downstream automatically without needing to be re-wired.\n\n④ This second AtlasBlockoutViewport has NO direct shot_cam wire at all — it inherits the merged solve's attached shot_cam and conforms to it anyway. Both viewports render at the SAME 1920x1080 (16:9) format despite the two branches starting from completely different geometry-derivation pipelines.\n\nIMPORTANT — what ShotCam does NOT change: it never touches how the source photo gets projected onto geometry (fx/fy/cx/cy/image_width/image_height, used by the projection shader's texture-sampling, stay exactly the solve's own values). Only the RENDER/VIEWING camera's format (resolution, aspect, FOV) conforms — 📽 Project still paints the original photo correctly regardless."
      ]
    }
